Dispersion parameter \(\phi = 38.06172\) which can be calculated based on m1 model:

pearson_r <- residuals(m1, type = "pearson")
sum(pearson_r^2)/m1$df.residual
[1] 38.06172

This means that the variance of residuals is 37 times larger than the mean, and thus we should adjust standard errors by 6.169418. So, lets check and compare standard errors from m2 with those from m1.

summary(summary(m2)$coef[,2]/summary(m1)$coef[,2])
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  6.169   6.169   6.169   6.169   6.169   6.169

Interpretation

  • Medium vs.Â Large Companies
    • \(\exp(\hat{\beta})\) = 0.136: The expected vacancies for Medium-sized companies is approximately 13.6% of that for Large companies, holding all other variables constant.
    • AME = -1.694: Medium-sized companies have, on average, 1.694 fewer vacancies compared to Large companies, holding all other factors constant.
  • Mazowieckie (14) vs.Â DolnoÅlÄskie (02):
    • \(\exp(\hat{\beta})\) = 2.022: The expected count in Mazowieckie province is approximately 2.02 times higher (or 102.2% higher) than in DolnoÅlÄskie province, holding all other variables constant.
    • AME = 1.193: The expected vacancies in Mazowieckie province is, on average, 1.193 higher than in DolnoÅlÄskie province, holding all other factors constant.
